BT 1 0 0 1 0 134 Tm 2.297318 Tw 12 TL /F1 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (Let's consider an example when there are many shared libraries, and where some of them support) Tj T* 0 Tw .042765 Tw (executors and some of them do not. Imagine that we have an application that uses a library like Threading) Tj T* 0 Tw -0.05439 Tw (Building Blocks \(TBB\) that \(in the future\) provides support for executors and another math library that does) Tj T* 0 Tw -0.048346 Tw (not support executors but uses TBB internally; an example of such a library is the Intel Math Kernel Library) Tj T* 0 Tw 1.013516 Tw (\(Intel MKL\). Assume that part of TBB's support for executors includes a way to specify the executor for) Tj T* 0 Tw 1.339213 Tw (algorithms like ) Tj /F3 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (parallel_for) Tj /F1 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (. If the application wants to change the executor for all ) Tj /F3 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (parallel_for) Tj /F1 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg  T* 0 Tw .831098 Tw (algorithms \(to add affinity, priority, etc.\), it can easily do this for its direct uses of ) Tj /F3 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (parallel_for) Tj /F1 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (. But it) Tj T* 0 Tw .968735 Tw (can only change the executors used for the ) Tj /F3 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (parallel_for) Tj /F1 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg ( algorithms in the math library if that library) Tj T* 0 Tw .431235 Tw (provides an interface to do so. The use of executors in the main application breaks composability, unless) Tj T* 0 Tw 1.517633 Tw (there is a standard way to communicate choices to nested uses. There should be a mechanism for a) Tj T* 0 Tw 1.352339 Tw (nested level to acquire a default execution context or the execution context it should use in its current) Tj T* 0 Tw (level.) Tj T* ET
