BT 1 0 0 1 0 158 Tm .70686 Tw 12 TL /F1 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (about the use of an execution context. As a motivating example, again imagine that we have application) Tj T* 0 Tw 2.433516 Tw (that uses TBB algorithms at the outer application level and a math library like MKL that uses TBB) Tj T* 0 Tw -0.020731 Tw (algorithms internally. By default, the TBB algorithms use a work-stealing task scheduler that typically leads) Tj T* 0 Tw .968555 Tw (to good nested composability. When using defaults, both the application and the MKL library algorithms) Tj T* 0 Tw .862339 Tw (can use TBB algorithms without being aware of each other and expect good performance. But what if a) Tj T* 0 Tw 3.149269 Tw (developer changes the default context for TBB algorithms to one that does not supported nested) Tj T* 0 Tw 2.56152 Tw (parallelism well? For example, they might choose to use OpenMP to execute TBB ) Tj /F3 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg (parallel_for) Tj /F1 10 Tf 0 0 0 rg  T* 0 Tw .468735 Tw (algorithms \(OpenMP has known composability issues but is often preferred in HPC due to its lower static) Tj T* 0 Tw .610697 Tw (scheduling overheads\). If the application and library use the same non-default execution context for TBB) Tj T* 0 Tw 2.113059 Tw (algorithms, and the execution context does not support nested parallelism well, the library developer) Tj T* 0 Tw .862339 Tw (needs to know the context of outside execution at run-time to make a correct decision about whether to) Tj T* 0 Tw 2.015318 Tw (use nested parallelism at all. Knowing about the outer execution context may be necessary to avoid) Tj T* 0 Tw .461318 Tw (oversubscription, dead \(live\) locks. etc. Even if an execution context correctly supports nesting, it may do) Tj T* 0 Tw (so inefficiently and so knowing the context may be critical from performance perspective.) Tj T* ET
